# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gdpr-technical-controls
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] Data portability applies to personal data.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] It involves access to personal data without implying data ownership per se.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] At the global level, there are proponents who see the protection of digital data as a human right.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] Thus, in an emerging civil society draft declaration, one finds mention of the following concepts and statutes: Right to Privacy on the Internet, Right to Digital Data Protection, Rights to Consumer Protection on the Internet – United Nations Guidelines for Consumer Protection.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] At the regional level, there are at least three main jurisdictions where data rights are seen differently: China and India, the United States, and the European Union.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] In the latter, personal data was given special protection under the 2018 General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR).
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] The GDPR thus became the fifth of the 24 types of legislation listed in Annex 1 Table of existing and proposed European Directives and Regulations in relation to data.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] Personal data are the basis for behavioral advertising, and early in the 21st century their value began to grow exponentially, at least as measured in the market capitalization of the major platforms holding personal data on their respective users.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] European Union regulators reacted to this perceived power imbalance between platforms and users, although much still hinges on the terms of consent given by users to the platforms.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] The concept of data portability comprises an attempt to correct the perceived power imbalance by introducing an element of competition allowing users to choose among platforms.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] With the advent of the General Data Protection Regulations (GDPR), social media platforms such as Twitter, Instagram, Snapchat, and the Wall Street Journal online subscriber community have widely adopted the ability to export and download user data into a ZIP archive file.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] Other platforms such as Google and Facebook were equipped with export options earlier.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] Some platforms restrict exports with time delays between each, such as once per 30 days on Twitter, and many platforms lack even partial export options.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] Other sites, such as Quora and Bumble, offer no automated request form, requiring the user to request a copy of their data through personal support email.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] Reputation portability refers to the ability of an individual to transfer their reputation or credibility from one context to another.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] This concept is becoming increasingly important in today's interconnected world, where individuals are involved in multiple online and offline communities.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] The idea behind reputation portability is that an individual's reputation should not be tied solely to a single community or platform.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] Rather, it should be transferable across different contexts, such as professional networks, social media platforms, and online marketplaces.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] This enables individuals to maintain a consistent reputation across various contexts, which can be beneficial in terms of building trust, and overcoming the so-called "cold-start" problem, and hence mitigating platform lock-in.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] Overall, reputation portability is an important concept in today's digital landscape, and research has shown that imported reputation can serve as viable signals for building trust.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] As technology continues to evolve, it is likely that reputation portability will become increasingly important in shaping how we interact with each other online and offline.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] Some mobile apps restrict data portability by storing user data in locked directories while lacking export options.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] Locked directories are inaccessible to an end-user without extraordinary measures such as so-called rooting (Android) or jailbreaking (iOS).
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] The former requires the so-called boot loader of the device to be in an unlocked state in advance, which it usually is not by default.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] Toggling that state involves a full erasure of all user data, known as the *wipe*, making it a vicious cycle if the user's aim were to access their locked data.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] Other mobile apps only allow the creation of user data backups using proprietary software provided by the vendor, lacking the ability to directly export the data to a local file in the mobile device's common user data directory.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] Such said software requires an external host computer to run on.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] Some device vendors offer cloud storage and synchronisation services for backing up data.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] Such services however require registration and depend on internet connection and preferably high internet speeds and data plan limits if used regularly.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] Some services may only allow moving parts of the data such as text messages and phone books between locked directories on devices of the same vendor (vendor lock-in), without the ability to export the information into local files directly accessible by the end user.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] Further possible restraints on data portability are poor reliability, stability and performance of existing means of data transfer, such as described in Media Transfer Protocol § Performance.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] Some digital video recorders (DVRs) which store recordings on an internal hard drive lack the ability to back up recordings, forcing a user to delete existing recordings upon exhausted disk space, which is an instance of poor data portability.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] Some DVRs have an operating system that depends on an Internet connection to boot and operate, meaning that recordings stored locally are inaccessible if no internet connection is available.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] If service for the device gets deprecated by the television service provider, the existing recordings become inaccessible and thus considerably lost.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] Cordless landline telephone units, as well as their associated base stations, which have firmwares with phone book and SMS messaging functionality, commonly lack an interface to connect to a computer for backing the data up.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] Some software such as the *Discourse* forum software offers a built-in ability for users to download their posts into an archive file.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] Other software may operate locally, but store user data in a proprietary format, thus causing vendor lock-in until successfully reverse-engineered by third party developers.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] The right to data portability was laid down in the European Union's General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) passed in April 2016.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] The regulation applies to data processors, whether inside or outside the EU, if they process data on individuals who are physically located within an EU member state.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] Earlier the European Data Protection Supervisor had stated that data portability could "let individuals benefit from the value created by the use of their personal data".
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] The European-level Article 29 Data Protection Working Party held a consultation on this in English lasting until the end of January 2017.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] The French national data supervisor CNIL hosted a discussion in French.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] Current participants offer opinions on how the legislation provides few benefits for companies, but many for users.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] In April 2017, new guidelines were published on the Article 29 Working Party website.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] In late 2019 the Data Governance Act was published by the Commission.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] In 2021 researchers, many of them French and Finnish, published a 46-page report covering the state-of-the-art.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] In 2022 the European Commission published the Data Act.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] Although the United Kingdom voted to withdraw from the EU, it intends to incorporate much of the GDPR in its own legislation, which will include data portability, as "...the GDPR itself contains some noteworthy innovations – for instance… the introduction of a new right to data portability".
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] In November at the Internet Governance Forum 2019 in Berlin panelists reported that Article 20 GDPR is not actionable, neither legally nor technically.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] In the UK—ironically post-Brexit—researchers are monitoring developments.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] Germany has called to strengthen the European Union's right to data portability using competition law.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] A commission was set up for the purpose of proposing improvements.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] Likewise, in Switzerland, a nation-state that is related to the EU only on a bilateral basis and as an EFTA member state, there has been a trend moving in the same direction.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] The Swiss view was officially published in March 2018 (as a document in PDF).
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] An association proposed to have a right to data portability anchored in the constitution of the Swiss Confederation.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] A law was passed that includes data portability; as described here in German and here in French.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] The association partners with a cooperative called MIDATA.coop, which will offer users a place to store their data.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] A second association has issued its guideline on the topic.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] Over the longer term, the Swiss may have to consider that data portability is in the GDPR.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] Given that the GDPR will raise compliance costs for EU-based companies, it is unlikely that the EU would tolerate a situation with third-party countries in which Swiss companies would not be held to the same standard in order to keep competition fair.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] The legal terms involved are adequacy and reciprocity.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] The State of California has a Consumer Privacy Act (CCPA) of 2018, which introduces data portability to the USA.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] The State of Utah is the first state to pass the Digital Choice Act, which, among other provisions, requires social media service providers of any size to provide data portability export (but not import) starting July 2026.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] Canada anticipates a law in that it shows Transparency, Portability and Interoperability as Principle No.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] Data portability is included in the Personal Data Protection Bill 2019 about to become law as section 26 in chapter VI.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] Data portability is included in the Privacy law#Brazil as its Article 18.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] In Australia, a Consumer Data Right has been proposed.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] Data portability is included in the new law.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] A right to data portability is enshrined in the new data protection law under clause 34.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] However, the intentions behind the new law, its enforcement and relation to the government's new Identity management system have already been contested.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] It is always tricky for legislators to regulate at the right level of precision, as everyone understands technology will evolve faster than the law.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] So far, only the European Union has formalized the expectations around data portability, requiring the data "in a structured, commonly used, machine-readable and interoperable format".
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] Likewise, European researchers stress that there are both practical and legal gaps that the EU should fill.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] The data portability right is slightly different from the Right of access to personal data; see GDPR and the seventh item in the list cited immediately above.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] The right of access only mandates that the data subject gets to see their personal data.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] The old EU Data Protection Directive used to require explicitly in such cases for the data to be provided in "intelligible" form, which has been interpreted so far as "human readable".
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] This requirement is still somewhat present in the EU's General Data Protection Regulation, but only implicitly in conjunction with Recital (law).
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] Since the right to portability is mostly concerned with reuse by other services (i.e. most likely automated), it could be that both "human readable" and "raw format" would be inappropriate for effective data portability.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] Some intermediate level might need to be sought.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] In addition, the GDPR limits the scope of data portability to cases where the processing is made on the basis of either consent of the data subject, or the performance of a contract.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] The data portability right is related to the "right to explanation", i.e. when automated decisions are made that have legal effect or significant impact on individual data subjects.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] One way to display an algorithm is through a decision tree.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] This right, however, was found to be not very useful in an empirical study.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] The right to explanation is related to the "Right to not be evaluated on the basis of automated processing" shown as the last item in the list shown in Gabel / Hickman.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] This includes decisions based on profiling.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] Such a right was included in the EU Data Protection Directive of 1995, but not much enforcement followed.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] An article in *Wired* emphasised the poignancy of the discussion.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] The issue has been discussed by Bygrave, and by Hildebrandt, who claimed this to be one of the most important transparency rights in the era of machine learning and big data.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] Contrary to Hildebrandt's high expectations in 2012, four years later, after many revisions to the GDPR, when the text was finalized, three other well-known authors contest whether a right to explanation still exists in the GDPR (see below).
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] In the United States there was a description of related developments in a seminal book by law professor Frank Pasquale; the relevant passages were reviewed by the Electronic Privacy Information Center (EPIC).
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency DARPA has an Explainable AI (XAI) program cited critically by blogger Artur Kiulian.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] Several papers have been published on these topics in 2016, the first of which, by Goodman / Flaxman, outlines the development of the right to explanation.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] Pasquale does not think the approach goes far enough, as he has stated in a blog entry at the London School of Economics (LSE).
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] In fact at LSE there is a whole series on Algorithmic Accountability of which that was one entry in Feb. of 2016, and other notable ones were by Joshua Kroll and Mireille Hildebrandt.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] A third 2016 paper, one co-authored by Mittelstadt et al., maps the literature and relates it to the GDPR on its pages 13–14.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] A fourth paper, one co-authored by Wachter, Mittelstadt and Floridi, refutes the idea that such a right might be included in the GDPR, proposes a limited 'right to be informed' instead and calls for the creation of an agency to implement the transparency requirement.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] Almost two years later a paper appeared that challenges earlier papers, especially Wachter / Mittelstadt / Floridi.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] On both sides of the Atlantic, there has been recent activity pertaining to this ongoing debate.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] Early in 2016 experts on artificial intelligence and UK government officials met during a number of meetings, and developed a Data Science Ethical Framework.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] On November 7, 2016 an event was held in Brussels, organized by MEP Marietje Schaake in the European Parliament and described by danah Boyd.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] Only eleven days later at New York University there was a conference on "Fairness, Accountability, and Transparency in Machine Learning " where Principles for Accountable Algorithms and a Social Impact Statement for Algorithms were articulated and placed online for discussion.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] By mid-December the IEEE came out with a document whose editing was backed up by public comments that were invited by March 2017 on "Ethically Aligned Design".
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-portability] Later in 2017 data portability was analysed by professors of data protection as a central innovation of the new GDPR.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-protection-impact-assessment] A **privacy impact assessment** (**PIA**) is a process which assists organizations in identifying and managing the privacy risks arising from new projects, initiatives, systems, processes, strategies, policies, business relationships etc.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-protection-impact-assessment] It benefits various stakeholders, including the organization itself and the customers, in many ways.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-protection-impact-assessment] In the United States and Europe, policies have been issued to mandate and standardize privacy impact assessments.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-protection-impact-assessment] A privacy impact assessment is a type of impact assessment conducted by an organization (typically, a government agency or corporation with access to a large amount of sensitive, private data about individuals in or flowing through its system).
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-protection-impact-assessment] The organization reviews its own processes to determine how these processes affect or might compromise the privacy of the individuals whose data it holds, collects, or processes.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-protection-impact-assessment] PIAs have been conducted by various sub-agencies of the U.S.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-protection-impact-assessment] Department of Homeland Security (DHS), and methods to conduct them have been standardized.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-protection-impact-assessment] Identify and evaluate the risks of privacy breaches or other incidents and effects.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-protection-impact-assessment] Identify appropriate privacy controls to mitigate unacceptable risks.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-protection-impact-assessment] A privacy impact report seeks to identify and record the essential components of any proposed system containing significant amounts of personal information and to establish how the privacy risks associated with that system can be managed.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-protection-impact-assessment] A PIA will sometimes go beyond an assessment of a "system" and consider critical "downstream" effects on people who are affected in some way by the proposal.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-protection-impact-assessment] Since PIA concerns an organization's ability to keep private information safe, the PIA should be completed whenever said organization is in possession of the personal information on its employees, clients, customers and business contacts etc.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-protection-impact-assessment] Although legal definitions vary, personal information typically includes a person's: name, age, telephone number, email address, sex, health information.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-protection-impact-assessment] A PIA should also be conducted whenever the organization possesses information that is otherwise sensitive, or if the security controls systems protecting private or sensitive information are undergoing changes that could lead to privacy incidents.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-protection-impact-assessment] Data Flow Analysis: mapping out how the proposed business process handles personal information, identifying clusters of personal information, and creating a diagram of how the personal information flows through the organization as a result of the business activities in question.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-protection-impact-assessment] Privacy Analysis: personnel involved with the movement of personal information may complete privacy analysis questionnaires, followed by reviews, interviews and discussions of the privacy issues and implications.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-protection-impact-assessment] Privacy Impact Assessment Report: the privacy risks and potential implications are documented, as well as a discussion of possible efforts that could be made in order to mitigate or remedy the risks.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-protection-impact-assessment] In the 1970s, the Technology Assessment (TA) was created by the United States Office of Technology Assessment.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-protection-impact-assessment] A TA was used to determine the societal and social repercussions of new technologies.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-protection-impact-assessment] Similarly, at around this time came the environmental impact assessments (EIA), a reaction to the social push from the sixties Green movements.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-protection-impact-assessment] The method of both of these impact assessments acted as precursors to the creation of the PIA.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-protection-impact-assessment] The "Privacy Impact Statement" was a much less extensive version of the PIA that came about in the late eighties.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-protection-impact-assessment] During the 1990s there became a need to measure the effectiveness of a company or organization's data security, especially with most data now being stored on computers or other electronic platforms.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-protection-impact-assessment] In addition several other countries and corporations use assessment systems similar to PIAs for data risk analysis.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-protection-impact-assessment] The E-Government Act of 2002, Section 208, established the requirement for agencies to conduct PIAs for electronic information systems and collections.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-protection-impact-assessment] The assessment is a practical method of evaluating privacy in information systems and collections, and documented assurance that privacy issues have been identified and adequately addressed.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-protection-impact-assessment] The European Commission signed its first Framework for Privacy Impact Assessments in the context of RFID Technology in 2011.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-protection-impact-assessment] This served as a basis to later recognize PIAs in the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), which in some cases now mandates data protection impact assessment (DPIA).
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-protection-impact-assessment] Aside from new IT systems and projects, the PIA approach has value for structured, periodic reviews or audits of an organization's privacy arrangements.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-protection-officer] A **data protection officer** (**DPO**) ensures within an organization that the laws protecting individuals' personal data are implemented.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-protection-officer] The designation, position and tasks of a DPO within an organization are described in Articles 37, 38 and 39 of the European Union (EU) General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR).
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-protection-officer] Many other countries require the appointment of a DPO, and it is becoming more prevalent in privacy legislation.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-protection-officer] The ability of a DPO to operate independently is considered to be "of utmost importance".
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-protection-officer] According to the GDPR, the DPO should report directly to the highest management level.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-protection-officer] This does not mean that the DPO has to be directly managed at this level, but they must have direct access to give advice to senior managers who are making decisions about personal data processing.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-protection-officer] The core responsibilities of the DPO include ensuring that his/her organization is aware of, and trained on, all relevant GDPR obligations.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-protection-officer] Common tasks of a DPO include ensuring proper processes are in place for subject access requests, data mapping, privacy impact assessments, as well as raising data privacy awareness with employees.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-protection-officer] Additionally, they must conduct audits to ensure compliance, address potential issues proactively, and act as a liaison between his/her organization and the public regarding all data privacy matters.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-protection-officer] In Germany, a 2001 law established a requirement for a DPO in certain organizations and included various protections around the scope and tenure for the role, including protections against dismissal for bringing problems to the attention of management.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/data-protection-officer] Many of these concepts were incorporated into the drafting of Article 38 of the GDPR and have continued to be incorporated in other privacy standards.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The **General Data Protection Regulation** (Regulation (EU) 2016/679), abbreviated **GDPR**, is a European Union regulation on information privacy in the European Union (EU) and the European Economic Area (EEA).
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The GDPR is an important component of EU privacy law and human rights law, in particular Article 8(1) of the Charter of Fundamental Rights of the European Union.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] It also governs the transfer of personal data outside the EU and EEA.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The GDPR's goals are to enhance individuals' control and rights over their personal information and to simplify the regulations for international business.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] It supersedes the Data Protection Directive 95/46/EC and, among other things, simplifies the terminology.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The European Parliament and Council of the European Union adopted the GDPR on 14 April 2016, to become effective on 25 May 2018.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] As an EU regulation (instead of a directive), the GDPR has direct legal effect and does not require transposition into national law.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] However, it also provides flexibility for individual member states to modify (derogate from) some of its provisions.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] As an example of the Brussels effect, the regulation became a model for many other laws around the world, including in Brazil, Japan, Singapore, South Africa, South Korea, Sri Lanka, and Thailand.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] After leaving the European Union, the United Kingdom enacted its "UK GDPR", identical to the GDPR.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The California Consumer Privacy Act (CCPA), adopted on 28 June 2018, has many similarities with the GDPR.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The GDPR also contains 173 recitals purposed to clarify scope and rationale for the regulatory provisions, as well as its legislative intents – Recital 4, for instance, begins by saying that the processing of personal data should be "designed to serve mankind".
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The regulation applies if the data controller, or processor, or the data subject (person) is based in the EU.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The regulation also applies to organisations based outside the EU if they collect or process personal data of individuals located inside the EU.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The regulation does not apply to the processing of data by private persons provided that the purpose has no connection to a professional or commercial activity." (Recital 18).
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] According to the European Commission, "Personal data is information that relates to an identified or identifiable individual.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] If you cannot directly identify an individual from that information, then you need to consider whether the individual is still identifiable.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The data protection reform package also includes a separate Data Protection Directive for the police and criminal justice sector that provides rules on personal data exchanges at State level, Union level, and international levels.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] A single set of rules applies to all EU member states.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Each member state establishes an independent supervisory authority (SA) to hear and investigate complaints, sanction administrative offences, etc.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] SAs in each member state co-operate with other SAs, providing mutual assistance and organising joint operations.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] If a business has multiple establishments in the EU, it must have a single SA as its "lead authority", based on the location of its "main establishment" where the main processing activities take place.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The lead authority thus acts as a "one-stop shop" to supervise all the processing activities of that business throughout the EU.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] A European Data Protection Board (EDPB) co-ordinates the SAs.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] EDPB thus replaces the **Article 29** Data Protection Working Party.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] There are exceptions for data processed in an employment context or in national security that still might be subject to individual country regulations.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] If informed *consent* is used as the lawful basis for processing, consent must have been explicit for data collected and each purpose data is used for.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Consent must be a specific, freely given, plainly worded, and unambiguous affirmation given by the data subject; an online form which has consent options structured as an opt-out selected by default is a violation of the GDPR, as the consent is not unambiguously affirmed by the user.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] In addition, multiple types of processing may not be "bundled" together into a single affirmation prompt, as this is not specific to each use of data, and the individual permissions are not freely given.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Data subjects must be allowed to withdraw this consent at any time, and the process of doing so must not be harder than it was to opt in.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] A data controller may not refuse service to users who decline consent to processing that is not strictly necessary in order to use the service.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Consent for children, defined in the regulation as being less than 16 years old (although with the option for member states to individually make it as low as 13 years old), must be given by the child's parent or custodian, and verifiable.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] If consent to processing was already provided under the Data Protection Directive, a data controller does not have to re-obtain consent if the processing is documented and obtained in compliance with the GDPR's requirements (Recital 171).
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The right of access (**Article 15**) is a data subject right.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] It gives people the right to access their personal data and information about how this personal data is being processed.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] A data subject must be able to transfer personal data from one electronic processing system to and into another, without being prevented from doing so by the data controller.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Data that has been sufficiently anonymised is excluded, but data that has been only de-identified but remains possible to link to the individual in question, such as by providing the relevant identifier, is not.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Both data being 'provided' by the data subject and data being 'observed', such as about behaviour, are included.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] In addition, the data must be provided by the controller in a structured and commonly used standard electronic format.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The right to data portability is provided by **Article 20**.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] A *right to be forgotten* was replaced by a more limited *right of erasure* in the version of the GDPR that was adopted by the European Parliament in March 2014.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] There are some instances where this objection does not apply.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] A task being carried out for public interest.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] GDPR is also clear that the data controller must inform individuals of their right to object from the first communication the controller has with them.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] This should be clear and separate from any other information the controller is providing and give them their options for how best to object to the processing of their data.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] There are instances the controller can refuse a request, in the circumstances that the objection request is "manifestly unfounded" or "excessive", so each case of objection must be looked at individually.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Other countries such as Canada are also, following the GDPR, considering legislation to regulate automated decision making under privacy laws, even though there are policy questions as to whether this is the best way to regulate AI.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] In the judgment *Österreichische Post* (C-300/21) the Court of Justice of the European Union gave an interpretation of the right to compensation.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Article 82(1) GDPR requires for the award of damages *(i)* an infringement of the GDPR, *(ii)* (actual) damage suffered and *(iii)* a causal link between the infringement and the damage suffered.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] It is not necessary that the damage suffered reaches a certain degree of seriousness.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] There is no European defined concept of damage.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Compensation is determined nationally in accordance with national law.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Data processors are only liable for damage caused by processing in breach of obligations specifically imposed on processors by the GDPR, or for damage caused by processing which is outside, or contrary to, the lawful instructions of the data controller.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Data controllers must clearly disclose any data collection, declare the lawful basis and purpose for data processing, and state how long data is being retained and if it is being shared with any third parties or outside of the EEA.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Firms have the obligation to protect data of employees and consumers to the degree where only the necessary data is extracted with minimum interference with data privacy from employees, consumers, or third parties.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Firms should have internal controls and regulations for various departments such as audit, internal controls, and operations.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Data subjects have the right to request a portable copy of the data collected by a controller in a common format, as well as the right to have their data erased under certain circumstances.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Public authorities, and businesses whose core activities consist of regular or systematic processing of personal data, are required to employ a *data protection officer* (DPO), who is responsible for managing compliance with the GDPR.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Data controllers must report data breaches to national supervisory authorities within 72 hours if they have an adverse effect on user privacy.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] In some cases, violators of the GDPR may be fined up to €20 million or up to 4% of the annual worldwide turnover of the preceding financial year in case of an enterprise, whichever is greater.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] To be able to demonstrate compliance with the GDPR, the data controller must implement measures that meet the principles of data protection by design and by default.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] **Article 25** requires data protection measures to be designed into the development of business processes for products and services.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Such measures include pseudonymising personal data, by the controller, as soon as possible (Recital 78).
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] It is the responsibility and the liability of the data controller to implement effective measures and be able to demonstrate the compliance of processing activities even if the processing is carried out by a data processor on behalf of the controller (Recital 74).
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] As such, the data subject must also be provided with contact details for the data controller and their designated data protection officer, where applicable.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Data protection impact assessments (**Article 35**) have to be conducted when specific risks occur to the rights and freedoms of data subjects.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Risk assessment and mitigation is required and prior approval of the data protection authorities is required for high risks.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] A report by the European Union Agency for Network and Information Security elaborates on what needs to be done to achieve privacy and data protection by default.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] It specifies that encryption and decryption operations must be carried out locally, not by remote service, because both keys and data must remain in the power of the data owner if any privacy is to be achieved.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The report specifies that outsourced data storage on remote clouds is practical and relatively safe if only the data owner, not the cloud service, holds the decryption keys.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] An example is encryption, which renders the original data unintelligible in a process that cannot be reversed without access to the correct decryption key.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The GDPR requires for the additional information (such as the decryption key) to be kept separately from the pseudonymised data.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Another example of pseudonymisation is tokenisation, which is a non-mathematical approach to protecting data at rest that replaces sensitive data with non-sensitive substitutes, referred to as tokens.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] While the tokens have no extrinsic or exploitable meaning or value, they allow for specific data to be fully or partially visible for processing and analytics while sensitive information is kept hidden.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Tokenisation does not alter the type or length of data, which means it can be processed by legacy systems such as databases that may be sensitive to data length and type.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] This also requires much fewer computational resources to process and less storage space in databases than traditionally encrypted data.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Pseudonymisation is a privacy-enhancing technology and is recommended to reduce the risks to the concerned data subjects and also to help controllers and processors to meet their data protection obligations (Recital 28).
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Such requirements may be modified by each EU country.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The records shall be in electronic form and the controller or the processor and, where applicable, the controller's or the processor's representative, shall make the record available to the supervisory authority on request.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Controllers and processors of personal data must put in place *appropriate technical and organizational measures* to implement the data protection principles.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Business processes that handle personal data must be designed and built with consideration of the principles and provide safeguards to protect data (for example, using pseudonymization or full anonymization where appropriate).
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Data controllers must design information systems with privacy in mind.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] For instance, using the highest-possible privacy settings by default, so that the datasets are not publicly available by default and cannot be used to identify a subject.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] No personal data may be processed unless this processing is done under one of the six lawful bases specified by the regulation (consent, contract, public task, vital interest, legitimate interest or legal requirement).
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] When the processing is based on consent the data subject has the right to revoke it at any time.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] A designated DPO can be a current member of staff of a controller or processor, or the role can be outsourced to an external person or agency through a service contract.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] In any case, the processing body must make sure that there is no conflict of interest in other roles or interests that a DPO may hold.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The contact details for the DPO must be published by the processing organisation (for example, in a privacy notice) and registered with the supervisory authority.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The DPO is similar to a compliance officer and is also expected to be proficient at managing IT processes, data security (including dealing with cyberattacks) and other critical business continuity issues associated with the holding and processing of personal and sensitive data.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The skill set required stretches beyond understanding legal compliance with data protection laws and regulations.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The DPO must maintain a living data inventory of all data collected and stored on behalf of the organization.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] More details on the function and the role of data protection officer were given on 13 December 2016 (revised 5 April 2017) in a guideline document.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Organisations based outside the EU must also appoint an EU-based person as a representative and point of contact for their GDPR obligations.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] This is a distinct role from a DPO, although there is overlap in responsibilities that suggest that this role can also be held by the designated DPO.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Article 42 and 43 of the GDPR set the legal basis for formal GDPR certifications.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] 42 GDPR, the purpose of this certification is to demonstrate “compliance with the GDPR of processing operations by controllers and processors”.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The GDPR certification also contributes to reduce the legal and financial risks of applicants, as well as of data controllers using certified data processing services.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The adoption of the European Data Protection Seals is under the responsibility of the European Data Protection Board (EDPB) and is recognized across all EU and EEA Member States.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] In October 2022, the Europrivacy certification criteria were officially recognized by the European Data Protection Board (EDPB) to serve as European Data Protection Seal.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Europrivacy was developed by the European research programme and is managed by the European Centre for Certification and Privacy (ECCP) in Luxembourg.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] These are some cases which are not addressed in the GDPR specifically, thus are treated as exemptions.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Conversely, an entity or more precisely an "enterprise" has to be engaged in "economic activity" to be covered by the GDPR.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Economic activity is defined broadly under European Union competition law.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The regulation applies regardless of where the processing takes place.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] This has been interpreted as intentionally giving GDPR extraterritorial jurisdiction for non-EU establishments if they are doing business with people located in the EU.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] It is questionable whether the EU or its member states will in practice be able to enforce GDPR against organisations which have no establishment in the EU.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Under **Article 27**, non-EU establishments subject to GDPR are obliged to have a designee within the European Union, an "EU Representative", to serve as a point of contact for their obligations under the regulation.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The EU Representative is the Controller's or Processor's contact person vis-à-vis European privacy supervisors and data subjects, in all matters relating to processing, to ensure compliance with this GDPR.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] A natural (individual) or legal (corporation) person can play the role of an EU Representative.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The non-EU establishment must issue a duly signed document (letter of accreditation) designating a given individual or company as its EU Representative.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The said designation can only be given in writing.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The intentional or negligent (willful blindness) character of the infringement (failure to designate an EU Representative) may rather constitute aggravating factors.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Non-EU public authorities and bodies are equally exempted.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Binding corporate rules, standard contractual clauses for data protection issued by a Data Processing Agreement (DPA), or a scheme of binding and enforceable commitments by the data controller or processor situated in a third country, are among examples.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The applicability of GDPR in the United Kingdom is affected by Brexit.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Although the United Kingdom formally withdrew from the European Union on 31 January 2020, it remained subject to EU law, including GDPR, until the end of the transition period on 31 December 2020.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Under the European Union (Withdrawal) Act 2018, existing and relevant EU law was transposed into UK law upon completion of the transition, and the GDPR was amended by statutory instrument to remove certain provisions no longer needed due to the UK's non-membership in the EU.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Thereafter, the regulation is referred to as "UK GDPR".
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The UK does not restrict the transfer of personal data to countries within the EEA under UK GDPR.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] As part of the withdrawal agreement, the European Commission committed to perform an adequacy assessment.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] On 28 June 2021, the Commission confirmed the adequacy of the UK GDPR for four years; This was set to expire on 27 June 2025, but was extended for six months to give the Commission time to assess the impact of the Data (Use and Access) Act 2025.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] On 19 December 2025 the Commission renewed the 2021 adequacy decision until 27 December 2031.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] In March 2021, Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport Oliver Dowden stated that the UK was exploring divergence from the EU GDPR in order to "[focus] more on the outcomes that we want to have and less on the burdens of the rules imposed on individual businesses".
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] As per a study conducted by Deloitte in 2018, 92% of companies believe they are able to comply with GDPR in their business practices in the long run.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Companies operating outside of the EU have invested heavily to align their business practices with GDPR.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The area of GDPR consent has a number of implications for businesses who record calls as a matter of practice.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] A typical disclaimer is not considered sufficient to gain assumed consent to record calls.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Additionally, when recording has commenced, should the caller withdraw their consent, then the agent receiving the call must be able to stop a previously started recording and ensure the recording does not get stored.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] IT professionals expect that compliance with the GDPR will require additional investment overall: over 80 percent of those surveyed expected GDPR-related spending to be at least US$100,000.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] It has been argued that smaller businesses and startup companies might not have the financial resources to adequately comply with the GDPR, unlike the larger international technology firms (such as Facebook and Google) that the regulation is ostensibly meant to target first and foremost.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] A lack of knowledge and understanding of the regulations has also been a concern in the lead-up to its adoption.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] A counter-argument to this has been that companies were made aware of these changes two years prior to them coming into effect and should have had enough time to prepare.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The regulations, including whether an enterprise must have a data protection officer, have been criticized for potential administrative burden and unclear compliance requirements.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] There is also concern regarding the implementation of the GDPR in blockchain systems, as the transparent and fixed record of blockchain transactions contradicts the very nature of the GDPR.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Many media outlets have commented on the introduction of a "right to explanation" of algorithmic decisions, but legal scholars have since argued that the existence of such a right is highly unclear without judicial tests and is limited at best.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The GDPR has garnered support from businesses who regard it as an opportunity to improve their data management.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Mark Zuckerberg has also called it a "very positive step for the Internet", and has called for GDPR-style laws to be adopted in the US.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Consumer rights groups such as The European Consumer Organisation are among the most vocal proponents of the legislation.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Other supporters have attributed its passage to the whistleblower Edward Snowden.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Free software advocate Richard Stallman has praised some aspects of the GDPR but called for additional safeguards to prevent technology companies from "manufacturing consent".
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Academic experts who participated in the formulation of the GDPR wrote that the law "is the most consequential regulatory development in information policy in a generation.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Despite having had at least two years to prepare and do so, many companies and websites changed their privacy policies and features worldwide directly prior to GDPR's implementation, and customarily provided email and other notifications discussing these changes.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Phishing scams also emerged using falsified versions of GDPR-related emails, and it was also argued that some GDPR notice emails may have actually been sent in violation of anti-spam laws.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] In March 2019, a provider of compliance software found that many websites operated by EU member state governments contained embedded tracking from ad technology providers.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] A blog, *GDPR Hall of Shame*, was also created to showcase unusual delivery of GDPR notices, and attempts at compliance that contained egregious violations of the regulation's requirements.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Its author remarked that the regulation "has a lot of nitty gritty, in-the-weeds details, but not a lot of information about how to comply", but also acknowledged that businesses had two years to comply, making some of its responses unjustified.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Research indicates that approximately 25% of software vulnerabilities have GDPR implications.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Since Article 33 emphasizes breaches, not bugs, security experts advise companies to invest in processes and capabilities to identify vulnerabilities before they can be exploited, including coordinated vulnerability disclosure processes.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] An investigation of Android apps' privacy policies, data access capabilities, and data access behaviour has shown that numerous apps display a somewhat privacy-friendlier behaviour since the GDPR was implemented, although they still retain most of their data access privileges in their code.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] An investigation of the Norwegian Consumer Council into the post-GDPR data subject dashboards on social media platforms (such as Google dashboard) has concluded that large social media firms deploy deceptive tactics in order to discourage their customers from sharpening their privacy settings.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Some companies, such as Klout, and several online video games, ceased operations entirely to coincide with its implementation, citing the GDPR as a burden on their continued operations, especially due to the business model of the former.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] The volume of online behavioural advertising placements in Europe fell 25–40% on 25 May 2018.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Facebook and subsidiaries WhatsApp and Instagram, as well as Google LLC (targeting Android), were immediately sued by Max Schrems's non-profit NOYB just hours after midnight on 25 May 2018, for their use of "forced consent".
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Schrems asserts that both companies violated Article 7(4) by not presenting opt-ins for data processing consent on an individualized basis, and requiring users to consent to all data processing activities (including those not strictly necessary) or would be forbidden from using the services.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] On 21 January 2019, Google was fined €50 million by the French DPA for showing insufficient control, consent, and transparency over use of personal data for behavioural advertising.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] In November 2018, following a journalistic investigation into Liviu Dragnea, the Romanian DPA (ANSPDCP) used a GDPR request to demand information on the RISE Project's sources.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] In July 2019, the British Information Commissioner's Office issued an intention to fine British Airways a record £183 million (1.5% of turnover) for poor security arrangements that enabled a 2018 web skimming attack affecting around 380,000 transactions.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] British Airways was ultimately fined a reduced amount of £20m, with the ICO noting that they had "considered both representations from BA and the economic impact of COVID-19 on their business before setting a final penalty".
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Critics interviewed by *Politico* also argued that enforcement was also being hampered by varying interpretations between member states, the prioritisation of guidance over enforcement by some authorities, and a lack of cooperation between member states.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] In November 2021, Irish Council for Civil Liberties lodged a formal complaint of the Commission that it is in breach of its obligation under EU Law to carefully monitor how Ireland applies the GDPR.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Until January 2023, the Commission published a new commitment based on the complaint of ICCL.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] While companies are now subject to legal obligations, there are still various inconsistencies in the practical and technical implementation of GDPR.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] As an example, according to the GDPR's right to access, the companies are obliged to provide data subjects with the data they gather about them.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] However, in a study on loyalty cards in Germany, companies did not provide the data subjects with the exact information of the purchased articles.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] One might argue that such companies do not collect the information of the purchased articles, which does not conform with their business models.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Therefore, data subjects tend to see that as a GDPR violation.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] As a result, studies have suggested for a better control through authorities.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] According to the GDPR, end-users' consent should be valid, freely given, specific, informed and active.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] However, the lack of enforceability regarding obtaining lawful consents has been a challenge.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] As an example, a 2020 study, showed that the Big Tech, i.e.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Google, Amazon, Facebook, Apple, and Microsoft (GAFAM), use dark patterns in their consent obtaining mechanisms, which raises doubts regarding the lawfulness of the acquired consent.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] In March 2021, EU member states led by France were reported to be attempting to modify the impact of the privacy regulation in Europe by exempting national security agencies.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] After around 160 million Euros in GDPR fines were imposed in 2020, the figure was already over one billion Euros in 2021.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] In 2024 and early 2025, GDPR enforcement actions intensified.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] The Irish Data Protection Commission (DPC) imposed a €345 million fine on TikTok for violations related to children's data privacy and insufficient safeguards for young users.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] In January 2025, Meta was fined €1.2 billion for unlawful data transfers between the EU and the US, marking one of the largest GDPR fines to date.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] On 12 February 2025, the European Commission abandoned proposed regulations on technology patents, AI liability, and privacy for messaging apps due to strong lobbying and a lack of consensus among EU lawmakers, with major tech firms opposing the changes.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Mass adoption of these new privacy standards by multinational companies has been cited as an example of the "Brussels effect", a phenomenon wherein European laws and regulations are used as a baseline due to their gravitas.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] The U.S. state of California passed the California Consumer Privacy Act on 28 June 2018, taking effect on 1 January 2020; it grants rights to transparency and control over the collection of personal information by companies in a similar means to GDPR.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Critics have argued that such laws need to be implemented at the federal level to be effective, as a collection of state-level laws would have varying standards that would complicate compliance.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Two other U.S. states have since enacted similar legislation: Virginia passed the Consumer Data Privacy Act on 2 March 2021, and Colorado enacted the Colorado Privacy Act on 8 July 2021.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] The Republic of Turkey, a candidate for European Union membership, adopted the Law on The Protection of Personal Data on 24 March 2016 in compliance with the EU acquis.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] China's 2021 Personal Information Protection Law is the country's first comprehensive law on personal data rights and is modelled after the GDPR.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Switzerland will also adopt a new data protection law that largely follows EU's GDPR.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] The CLOUD Act, enacted in 2018, is seen by the European Data Protection Supervisor (EDPS) as a law in possible conflict with the GDPR.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] A 2024 study found that GDPR reduced both EU user website page views and website revenue by 12%.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] The EU Digital Single Market strategy relates to "digital economy" activities related to businesses and people in the EU.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] As part of the strategy, the GDPR and the NIS Directive all apply from 25 May 2018.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] The proposed ePrivacy Regulation was also planned to be applicable from 25 May 2018, but will be delayed for several months.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] The eIDAS Regulation is also part of the strategy.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] In an initial assessment, the European Council has stated that the GDPR should be considered "a prerequisite for the development of future digital policy initiatives".
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] Recent developments in computer science and data engineering, such as support for encoding privacy in data and the availability and quality of Privacy-Enhancing Technologies (PET's) partly offset those critiques and help to make the principles feasible in real-world settings.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] The European GDPR regulation incorporates privacy by design.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] The privacy by design framework was developed by Ann Cavoukian, Information and Privacy Commissioner of Ontario, following her joint work with the Dutch Data Protection Authority and the Netherlands Organisation for Applied Scientific Research in 1995.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] In 2009, the Information and Privacy Commissioner of Ontario co-hosted an event, *Privacy by Design: The Definitive Workshop*, with the Israeli Law, Information and Technology Authority at the 31st International Conference of Data Protection and Privacy Commissioners (2009).
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] In 2010 the framework achieved international acceptance when the International Assembly of Privacy Commissioners and Data Protection Authorities unanimously passed a resolution on privacy by design recognising it as an international standard at their annual conference.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] Among other commitments, the commissioners resolved to promote privacy by design as widely as possible and foster the incorporation of the principle into policy and legislation.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] The principles have been cited in over five hundred articles referring to the *Privacy by Design in Law, Policy and Practice* white paper by Ann Cavoukian.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] The privacy by design approach is characterized by proactive rather than reactive measures.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] It anticipates and prevents privacy invasive events before they happen.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] Privacy by design does not wait for privacy risks to materialize, nor does it offer remedies for resolving privacy infractions once they have occurred — it aims to prevent them from occurring.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] In short, privacy by design comes before-the-fact, not after.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] Privacy by design seeks to deliver the maximum degree of privacy by ensuring that personal data are automatically protected in any given IT system or business practice.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] If an individual does nothing, their privacy still remains intact.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] No action is required on the part of the individual to protect their privacy — it is built into the system, by default.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] Privacy by design is embedded into the design and architecture of IT systems as well as business practices.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] It is not bolted on as an add-on, after the fact.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] The result is that privacy becomes an essential component of the core functionality being delivered.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] Privacy is integral to the system without diminishing functionality.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] Privacy by design seeks to accommodate all legitimate interests and objectives in a positive-sum “win-win” manner, not through a dated, zero-sum approach, where unnecessary trade-offs are made.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] Privacy by design avoids the pretense of false dichotomies, such as privacy versus security, demonstrating that it is possible to have both.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] Privacy by design, having been embedded into the system prior to the first element of information being collected, extends securely throughout the entire lifecycle of the data involved — strong security measures are essential to privacy, from start to finish.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] This ensures that all data are securely retained, and then securely destroyed at the end of the process, in a timely fashion.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] Thus, privacy by design ensures cradle-to-grave, secure lifecycle management of information, end-to-end.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] Privacy by design seeks to assure all stakeholders that whatever business practice or technology involved is in fact operating according to the stated promises and objectives, subject to independent verification.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] The component parts and operations remain visible and transparent, to users and providers alike.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] Above all, privacy by design requires architects and operators to keep the interests of the individual uppermost by offering such measures as strong privacy defaults, appropriate notice, and empowering user-friendly options.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] The International Organization for Standardization (ISO) approved the Committee on Consumer Policy (COPOLCO) proposal for a new ISO standard: *Consumer Protection: Privacy by Design for Consumer Goods and Services* (ISO/PC317).
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] The standard will aim to specify the design process to provide consumer goods and services that meet consumers’ domestic processing privacy needs as well as the personal privacy requirements of data protection.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] The standard has the UK as secretariat with thirteen participating members and twenty observing members.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] The Standards Council of Canada (SCC) is one of the participating members and has established a mirror Canadian committee to ISO/PC317.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] The OASIS Privacy by Design Documentation for Software Engineers (PbD-SE) Technical Committee provides a specification to operationalize privacy by design in the context of software engineering.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] Privacy by design, like security by design, is a normal part of the software development process and a risk reduction strategy for software engineers.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] The PbD-SE specification translates the PbD principles to conformance requirements within software engineering tasks and helps software development teams to produce artifacts as evidence of PbD principle adherence.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] Privacy by design originated from privacy-enhancing technologies (PETs) in a joint 1995 report by Ann Cavoukian and John Borking.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] In 2007 the European Commission provided a memo on PETs.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] In 2008 the British Information Commissioner's Office commissioned a report titled *Privacy by Design – An Overview of Privacy Enhancing Technologies*.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] There are many facets to privacy by design.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] There is the technical side like software and systems engineering, administrative elements (e.g. legal, policy, procedural), other organizational controls, and operating contexts.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] Privacy by design evolved from early efforts to express fair information practice principles directly into the design and operation of information and communications technologies.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] In his publication *Privacy by Design: Delivering the Promises* Peter Hustinx acknowledges the key role played by Ann Cavoukian and John Borking, then Deputy Privacy Commissioners, in the joint 1995 publication *Privacy-Enhancing Technologies: The Path to Anonymity*.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] This 1995 report focussed on exploring technologies that permit transactions to be conducted anonymously.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] Privacy-enhancing technologies allow online users to protect the privacy of their Personally Identifiable Information (PII) provided to and handled by services or applications.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] Privacy by design evolved to consider the broader systems and processes in which PETs were embedded and operated.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] Center for Democracy & Technology (CDT) in *The Role of Privacy by Design in Protecting Consumer Privacy* distinguishes PET from privacy by design noting that “PETs are most useful for users who already understand online privacy risks.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] 4 *Teledienstedatenschutzgesetz* [Teleservices Data Protection Act]) in July 1997.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] The new EU General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) includes ‘data protection by design’ and ‘data protection by default’, the second foundational principle of privacy by design.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] Canada's Privacy Commissioner included privacy by design in its report on *Privacy, Trust and Innovation – Building Canada's Digital Advantage*.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] In Australia, the Commissioner for Privacy and Data Protection for the State of Victoria (CPDP) has formally adopted privacy by design as a core policy to underpin information privacy management in the Victorian public sector.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] The UK Information Commissioner's Office website highlights privacy by design and data protection by design and default.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] In October 2014, the Mauritius Declaration on the Internet of Things was made at the 36th International Conference of Data Protection and Privacy Commissioners and included privacy by design and default.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] The Privacy Commissioner for Personal Data, Hong Kong held an educational conference on the importance of privacy by design.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] In the private sector, Sidewalk Toronto commits to privacy by design principles; Brendon Lynch, Chief Privacy Officer at Microsoft, wrote an article called *Privacy by Design at Microsoft*; whilst Deloitte relates certifiably trustworthy to privacy by design.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] The privacy by design framework attracted academic debate, particularly following the 2010 International Data Commissioners resolution that provided criticism of privacy by design with suggestions by legal and engineering experts to better understand how to apply the framework into various contexts.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] Privacy by design has been critiqued as "vague" and leaving "many open questions about their application when engineering systems." Suggestions have been made to instead start with and focus on minimizing data, which can be done through security engineering.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] Leuven published Engineering Privacy by Design noting that “The design and implementation of privacy requirements in systems is a difficult problem and requires translation of complex social, legal and ethical concerns into systems requirements”.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] The principles of privacy by design "remain vague and leave many open questions about their application when engineering systems".
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] The authors argue that "starting from data minimization is a necessary and foundational first step to engineer systems in line with the principles of privacy by design".
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] This is partly a more structural problem due to the fact that legal principles are abstract, open-ended with different possible interpretations and exceptions, whereas engineering practices require unambiguous meanings and formal definitions of design concepts.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] In 2011, the Danish National It and Telecom Agency published a discussion paper in which they argued that privacy by design is a key goal for creating digital security models, by extending the concept to "Security by Design".
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] The objective is to balance anonymity and surveillance by eliminating identification as much as possible.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] Another criticism is that current definitions of privacy by design do not address the methodological aspect of systems engineering, such as using decent system engineering methods, e.g. those which cover the complete system and data life cycle.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] This problem is further exacerbated in the move to networked digital infrastructures initiatives such as the smart city or the Internet of Things.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] Whereas privacy by design has mainly been focused on the responsibilities of singular organisations for a certain technology, these initiatives often require the interoperability of many different technologies operated by different organisations.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] This requires a shift from organisational to infrastructural design.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] The concept of privacy by design also does not focus on the role of the actual data holder but on that of the system designer.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] This role is not known in privacy law, so the concept of privacy by design is not based on law.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] This, in turn, undermines the trust by data subjects, data holders and policy-makers.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] Questions have been raised from science and technology studies of whether privacy by design will change the meaning and practice of rights through implementation in technologies, organizations, standards and infrastructures.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] From a civil society perspective, some have even raised the possibility that a bad use of these design-based approaches can even lead to the danger of bluewashing.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] This refers to the minimal instrumental use by organizations of privacy design without adequate checks, in order to portray themselves as more privacy-friendly than is factually justified.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] It has also been pointed out that privacy by design is similar to voluntary compliance schemes in industries impacting the environment, and thus lacks the teeth necessary to be effective, and may differ per company.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] In addition, the evolutionary approach currently taken to the development of the concept will come at the cost of privacy infringements because evolution implies also letting unfit phenotypes (privacy-invading products) live until they are proven unfit.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] Some critics have pointed out that certain business models are built around customer surveillance and data manipulation and therefore voluntary compliance is unlikely.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] In 2013, Rubinstein and Good used Google and Facebook privacy incidents to conduct a counterfactual analysis in order to identify lessons learned of value for regulators when recommending privacy by design.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] The first was that “more detailed principles and specific examples” would be more helpful to companies.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] The second is that “usability is just as important as engineering principles and practices”.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] The third is that there needs to be more work on “refining and elaborating on design principles–both in privacy engineering and usability design”. including efforts to define international privacy standards.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] The final lesson learned is that "regulators must do more than merely recommend the adoption and implementation of privacy by design".
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] Rubinstein and Good also highlighted that privacy by design could result in applications that exemplified Privacy by Design and their work was well received.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] The following sections of this opinion provide an overview of relevant developments and recommend further efforts".
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] The European Data Protection Supervisor Giovanni Buttarelli set out the requirement to implement privacy by design in his article.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] The European Union Agency for Network and Information Security (ENISA) provided a detailed report *Privacy and Data Protection by Design – From Policy to Engineering* on implementation.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] The Summer School on real-world crypto and privacy provided a tutorial on "Engineering Privacy by Design".
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] The OWASP Top 10 Privacy Risks Project for web applications that gives hints on how to implement privacy by design in practice.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] The OASIS Privacy by Design Documentation for Software Engineers (PbD-SE) offers a privacy extension/complement to OMG's Unified Modeling Language (UML) and serves as a complement to OASIS’ eXtensible Access Control Mark-up Language (XACML) and Privacy Management Reference Model (PMRM).
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] Privacy by Design guidelines are developed to operationalise some of the high-level privacy-preserving ideas into more granular actionable advice., such as recommendations on how to implement privacy by design into existing (data) systems.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/privacy-by-design] However, still the applications of privacy by design guidelines by software developers remains a challenge.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] The **right to be forgotten** (**RTBF**) is the right to have private information about a person removed from Internet searches and other directories in some circumstances.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] The issue arose from the desires of individuals to "determine the development of their life in an autonomous way, without being perpetually or periodically stigmatized as a consequence of a specific action performed in the past".
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] The right entitles a person to have data about them deleted so that it can no longer be discovered by third parties, particularly through search engines.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Those who favor a right to be forgotten cite its necessity due to issues such as revenge porn sites and references to past petty crimes appearing in search engine listings for a person's name.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] The main concern is for the potentially undue influence that such results may exert upon a person's online reputation indefinitely if not removed.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Those who oppose the right worry about its effect on the right to freedom of expression and whether creating a right to be forgotten would result in a decreased quality of the Internet, censorship, and the rewriting of history.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] The right to be forgotten is distinct from the right to privacy.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] The right to privacy constitutes information that is not known publicly, whereas the right to be forgotten involves revoking public access to information that was known publicly at a certain time.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Argentina has had lawsuits by celebrities against Google and Yahoo! in which the plaintiffs demand the removal of certain search results, and require removal of links to photographs.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] One case, brought by artist Virginia da Cunha, involved photographs which had originally been taken with her permission and uploaded with her permission, however she alleged that the search results improperly associated her photographs with pornography.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Da Cunha's case achieved initial success resulting in Argentina search engines not showing images of the particular celebrity, however, this decision is on appeal.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Virginia Simari, the judge in favor of Da Cunha, stated that people have the right to control their image and avert others from "capturing, reproducing, broadcasting, or publishing one's image without permission".
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Argentina's efforts to protect their people's right to be forgotten has been called "the most complete" because individuals are able to correct, delete, or update information about themselves: overall, their information is bound to remain confidential.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] In 2016, a Chinese court in Beijing rejected an argument for the right to be forgotten when a judge ruled in favor of Baidu in a lawsuit over removing search results.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] It was the first of such cases to be heard in Chinese court.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] In the suit, Ren Jiayu sued Chinese search engine Baidu over search results that negatively associated him with a previous employer, Wuxi Taoshi Biotechnology.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Ren argued that by posting the search results, Baidu had infringed upon his right of name and right of reputation, both protected under Chinese law.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Because of these protections, Ren believed he had a right to be forgotten by removing these search results.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] The court ruled against Ren, claiming his name is a collection of common characters and as a result the search results were derived from relevant words.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] The court described search results as neutral findings based on an algorithm and stated that retaining such information was necessary for the public.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] As the call for personal information protection has grown louder, China has taken active measures to strengthen data protection.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] In 2018, China released the national standard "Information Security Technology—Personal Information Security Specification," which was the first systematic regulation for personal information protection.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] In 2020, the updated national standards replaced the version that came into effect in 2018.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Subsequently, in 2021, China introduced the formal legal framework, the "Personal Information Protection Law of the People's Republic of China" (PIPL).
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] The enactment of this law filled a legal gap and made detailed provisions regarding the collection, storage, use, transfer, and deletion of personal information.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] For businesses, it is essential to follow the principles of legality, fairness, and necessity when collecting and using personal data, ensuring transparency and data security.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Moreover, the PIPL strengthens the regulation of cross-border data flows, requiring risk assessments in specific cases and mandating additional protective measures for users.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Europe's data protection laws do not implement a "right to be forgotten", but a more limited "right to [data] erasure".
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Although the term "right to be forgotten" is a relatively new idea, the European Court of Justice legally solidified that the "right to be forgotten" is a human right when they ruled against Google in the *Costeja* case on May 13, 2014.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] This raises questions about the limitations of application in a jurisdiction include the inability to require removal of information possessed by companies outside the jurisdiction.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] There is no global framework to allow individuals control over their online image.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] In 1995, the European Union adopted the European Data Protection Directive (Directive 95/46/EC) to regulate the processing of personal data.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Data protection is now considered a component of human rights law.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] The European General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), in force since 2018, provides protection and exemption for companies listed as "media" companies, like newspapers and other journalistic work.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] However, Google purposely opted out of being classified as a "media" company, therefore the company is not protected.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Judges in the European Union ruled that because the international corporation, Google, is a collector and processor of data it should be classified as a "data controller" under the meaning of the EU data protection directive.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] These "data controllers" are required under EU law to remove data that is "inadequate, irrelevant, or no longer relevant", making this directive of global importance.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] In Article 12 of the Directive 95/46/EC the EU gave a legal basis to Internet protection for individuals.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] A *right to be forgotten* was replaced by a more limited *right of erasure* in Article 17 of the GDPR, which came into force in May 2018.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] To exercise the right to be forgotten and request removal from a search engine, one must complete a form through the search engine's website.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Google's removal request process requires the applicant to identify their country of residence, personal information, a list of the URLs to be removed along with a short description, and – in some cases – attachment of legal identification.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] The applicant receives an email from Google confirming the request but the request must be assessed before it is approved for removal.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] If the request is approved, searches using the individual's name will no longer result in the content appearing in search results.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] The content remains online and is not erased.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] After a request is filled, their removals team reviews the request, weighing "the individual's right to privacy against the public's right to know", deciding if the website is "inadequate, irrelevant or no longer relevant, or excessive in relation to the purposes for which they were processed".
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Google has formed an Advisory Council of various professors, lawyers, and government officials from around Europe to provide guidelines for these decisions.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] However, the review process is still a mystery to the general public.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Guidelines set by EU regulators were not released until November 2014, but Google began to take action on this much sooner than that, which (according to one author) allowed them "to shape interpretation to [their] own ends".
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] In May 2015, eighty academics called for more transparency from Google in an open letter.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] The form asks people to select one of the 27 countries that make up the European Union, as well as Andorra, Iceland, Liechtenstein, Monaco, Norway, San Marino, Switzerland, and the United Kingdom, plus several dependent territories.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] "The form allows an individual or someone representing an individual to put in a request" for the removal of any URLs believed to be a violation of the individual's privacy.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Regardless of who is submitting the form, some form of photo identification of the person the form is being submitted for must be present.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] This is meant to serve as proof that the person for whom the request was made for does in fact approve.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] If Google refuses a request to delink material, Europeans can appeal to their local data protection agency.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] As of May 2015, the British Information Commissioner's Office (ICO) had treated 184 such complaints, and overturned Google's decision in about a quarter of those.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] If Google fails to comply with a decision of the ICO, it can face legal action.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Google indeed acknowledged that some of its search result removals, affecting articles that were of public interest, were incorrect, and reinstated the links a week later.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Google notifies websites that have URLs delinked, and various news organizations, such as BBC, have published lists of delinked articles.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Complainants have been named in news commentary regarding those delinkings.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] In August 2015 the ICO issued an enforcement action requiring Google to delink some of these more recent articles from searches for a complainant's name, after Google refused to do so.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Some academics have criticized news organizations and Google for their behavior.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] In July 2015, Google accidentally revealed data on delinkings that "shows 95% of Google privacy requests are from citizens out to protect personal and private information – not criminals, politicians and public figures." Only 5% of requests were made by criminals, politicians, and public figures.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] One request for data removal was from a British doctor requesting to have 50 links removed on past botched medical procedures.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Google agreed to remove three search results containing his personal information.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] The European Union has been advocating for the delinkings requested by EU citizens to be implemented by Google not just in European versions of Google (as in google.co.uk, google.fr, etc.), but on google.com and other international subdomains.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Regulators want delinkings to be implemented so that the law cannot be circumvented in any way.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Google has refused the French Data Protection Agency's demand to apply the right internationally.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Due in part to their refusal to comply with the recommendation of the privacy regulating board Google has become the subject of a four-year-long antitrust investigation by the European Commission.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] In September 2015, the French Data Protection Agency dismissed Google's appeal.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] The French Data Protection Agency appealed to the EU courts to seek action on Google for failing to delink in its global servers.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] As of September 2015, the most delinked site is *www.facebook.com*.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Three of Google's own sites, *groups.google.com*, *plus.google.com* and *www.youtube.com* are among the ten most delinked sites.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] In addition to Google, Yahoo! and Bing have also made forms available for making delinking requests.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] In September 2019, the European Court of Justice ruled that the right to be forgotten did not apply outside of its member states.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] The ruling meant that Google did not have to delete the names of individuals from all of its international versions.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] They do not however need to obtain explicit consent before indexing such data, even though the law typically requires explicit consent before data processing, on the basis that such examination would not be within the powers, responsibiities or capabilities of a search engine.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] The consequences of this judgment have been criticised in data protection scholarship, as its logic implies that technologies that are designed in a way that renders data protection compliance impossible may be given the right to avoid the law.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] In December 2022, the judges in Luxembourg further extended the right to be forgotten in the case C-460/20 *TU, RE v Google LLC*.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] The case related to two managers of a group of investment companies, who argued that three unflattering news articles should be 'de-referenced' from the search engine results of Google, when searching for their names.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] They claimed that the information presented in the articles was wrong factually, which raised the question whether search engine operators need to check the accuracy of the information.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Additionally, the applicants required that photographs showing them in preview images – or thumbnails – when carrying out a search ought to be removed.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] In this judgment the European Court of Justice largely agreed with the request of the applicants.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Search engine operators such as Google are required to de-reference the respective information, if a person who seeks de-referencing submits 'relevant and sufficient' evidence capable of substantiating his or her request, and thereby manifests the inaccuracy of the information found (para.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] For thumbnails an independent assessment must be performed, but essentially the same thinking applies.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Europe's jurisdiction of data also extends beyond its borders into countries that does not have "adequate" protections.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] For instance, Europe's transfer of data to vulnerable countries are limited, resulting in companies like Google and Amazon establishing European data centers to quarantine data from Europe.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] He initially attempted to have the article removed by complaining to the Spanish Data Protection Agency, which rejected the claim on the grounds that it was lawful and accurate, but accepted a complaint against Google and asked Google to remove the results.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Google sued in the Spanish *Audiencia Nacional* (National High Court) which referred a series of questions to the European Court of Justice.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] The court ruled that search engines are responsible for the content they point to and thus, Google was required to comply with EU data privacy laws.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] On its first day of compliance only (May 30, 2014), Google received 12,000 requests to have personal details removed from its search engine.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Stopp, attorney for Werlé and Lauber, had won a default judgment in German court, on behalf of Lauber, against the Wikimedia Foundation.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] According to the Electronic Frontier Foundation, Werlé's lawyers also challenged an Internet service provider in Austria which published the names of the convicted killers.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Wikimedia is based in the United States, where the First Amendment protects freedom of speech and freedom of the press.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] In Germany, the law seeks to protect the name and likenesses of private persons from unwanted publicity.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] On January 18, 2008, a court in Hamburg supported the personality rights of Werlé, which by German law includes removing his name from archive coverage of the case.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] On November 12, 2009, *The New York Times* reported that Wolfgang Werlé had a case pending against the Wikimedia Foundation in a German court.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] The editors of the German-language Wikipedia article about Sedlmayr removed the names of the murderers, which have since then been restored to the article.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] *The Guardian* observed that the lawsuit has resulted in the Streisand effect, an upsurge in publicity for the case resulting from the legal action.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] On December 15, 2009, the German Federal Court of Justice (*Bundesgerichtshof*) in Karlsruhe ruled that German websites do not have to check their archives in order to provide permanent protection of personality rights for convicted criminals.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] The case occurred after the names of the brothers were found on the website of *Deutschlandradio*, in an archive article dating from July 2000.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] The presiding judge Gregor Galke stated "This is not a blank check", and stated that the right to rehabilitation of offenders had been taken into consideration.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] On November 28, 2019, the federal constitutional court in Karlsruhe ruled that German murderer Paul Termann had the right to be forgotten.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] The 2012 draft European Data Protection Regulation Article 17 detailed the "right to be forgotten and to erasure".
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] The EU defines "data controllers" as "people or bodies that collect and manage personal data".
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Where the controller has authorized a third party publication of personal data, the controller shall be considered responsible for that publication".
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] In the situation that a data controller does not take all reasonable steps then they will be fined heavily.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] The European Parliament was once "expected to adopt the proposals in first reading in the April 2013 Plenary session".
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] The right to be forgotten was replaced by a more limited right to erasure in the version of the GDPR adopted by the European Parliament in March 2014.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] The European Union is an influential group of states, and this tendency towards the right to be forgotten in the EU is an indicator of its recognition globally as a right.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] To support this, in 2012 the Obama Administration released a "Privacy Bill of Rights" to protect consumers online.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] In June 2014, Privacy Commissioner Allan Chiang Yam-wang (蔣任宏) expressed his support for introducing the right to be forgotten to Hong Kong.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Opposition expressed their worry that the right would inhibit freedom of information, and introducing erase from history.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Charles Mok, Hong Kong Legislative Councillor from I.T. occupation, oppose to introduce the right to be forgotten, citing the difficulty of enforcing and abuses of practising the right.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] He described the abuses as "right to be deleteion" In July 2015, Stephen Wong Kai-yi (黃繼兒) replaced Chiang's position and promised not to introduce the right to be forgotten.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] In April 2016, the Delhi High Court began to examine the issue after a Delhi banker requested to have his personal details removed from search results after a marital dispute.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] In this case, due to the dispute being settled, the banker's request is valid.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] The High Court has asked for a reply from Google and other search engine companies by September 19, upon which the court will continue to investigate the issue.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] In January 2017, the Karnataka High Court upheld the right to be forgotten, in a case involving a woman who originally went to court in order to get a marriage certificate annulled, claiming to have never been married to the man on the certificate.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] After the two parties came to an agreement, the woman's father wanted her name to be removed from search engines regarding criminal cases in the high court.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] The Karnataka High Court approved the father's request, stating that she had a right to be forgotten.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] As of February 2017, the Delhi High Court is hearing a case involving a man requesting to have information regarding his mother and wife to be removed from a search engine.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] The man believes that having his name linked to the search is hindering his employment options.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] The Delhi High Court is still working on the case, along with the issue of whether or not a right to be forgotten should be a legal standard in India.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Currently, there is no legal standard for the right to be forgotten, but if implemented, this would mean that citizens no longer need to file a case in order to request for information from search engines to be removed.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] This case could have significant impacts on the right to be forgotten and search engines in India.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] In May 2016, South Korea's Communications Commission (KCC) announced citizens will be able to request search engines and website administrators to restrict their own postings from being accessible publicly.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] The KCC released "Guidelines on the Right to Request Access Restrictions on Personal Internet Postings", which took effect in June 2016 and do not apply to third party contents.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] To the extent that the right to be forgotten concerns a data subject's right to limit the searchability of third party postings about him/her, the Guideline does not constitute a right to be forgotten.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] The guidelines created by the KCC include that data subjects can remove content that includes the URL links, and any evidence consisting of personal information.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] The commission included different amendments to the guideline.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] This includes describing the Guidelines as a "minimum" and "preliminary" precaution regarding privacy rights in vague areas of existing laws.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] The guideline encompasses foreign Internet companies that provide translation services for South Korean consumers.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] In order to have a person's information "forgotten" he or she has to go through a three step process: the issue posted with the URL, proof of ownership of the post, grounds for the request.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] When posting the URL, the web operator has the right to preserve the posting issue.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] The second being that if the post is relevant to public interest, web operators will process this request on the terms of relevance.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] The right to be forgotten was added in the constitution of the Canton of Geneva in the new article 21A *right to digital integrity* voted on June 18, 2023.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Consideration of the right to be forgotten occurred in US case law, specifically in *Melvin v.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Reid* (1931), an ex-prostitute was charged with murder and then acquitted; she subsequently tried to assume a quiet and anonymous place in society.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] However, the 1925 movie *The Red Kimono* revealed her history, and she successfully sued the producer.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] FR Publishing Corp.* (1940), the plaintiff, William James Sidis, was a former child prodigy who wished to spend his adult life quietly, without recognition; however, this was disrupted by an article in *The New Yorker*.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] The court held here that there were limits to the right to control one's life and facts about oneself, and held that there is social value in published facts, and that a person cannot ignore their celebrity status merely because they want to.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] These criticisms are consistent with the proposal that the only information that can be removed by user's request is content that they themselves uploaded.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] In a June 2014 opinion piece in *Forbes*, columnist Joseph Steinberg noted that "many privacy protections that Americans believe that they enjoy – even some guaranteed by law – have, in fact, been eroded or even obliterated by technological advances".
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] On March 11, 2015, Intelligence Squared US, an organization that stages Oxford-Style debates, held an event concerning the question, "Should the U.S. adopt the 'Right to be Forgotten' online?" The side against the motion won with a 56% majority of the voting audience.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] While opinions among experts are divided in the U.S., one survey indicated that 9 in 10 Americans want some form of the right to be forgotten.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] The consumer rights organization Consumer Watchdog has filed a complaint with the Federal Trade Commission for Americans to obtain the right as well.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] In June 2018, California enacted the California Consumer Privacy Act, providing consumers with the right to delete their personal information from covered businesses.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] In October 2023, the state enacted the California Delete Act, requiring the California Privacy Protection Agency to establish a one-stop shop deletion mechanism for consumers to direct data brokers to delete their personal information.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] In January 2021, the *Boston Globe* announced a program to allow subjects of relatively inconsequential stories to have the stories contextualized, removed from Google searches or anonymized.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] In January 2025, it was reported that *The Oregonian, The Plain Dealer, Bangor Daily News, The Atlanta Journal-Constitution* and NJ.com offered similar services.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] The regulatory differences in the protection of personal data between countries has real impact on international relations.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] The right to be forgotten, specifically, is a matter of EU-US relations when applied to cross-border data flow, as it raises questions about territorial sovereignty.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] The structure of the Westphalian international system assumes that the reach of a country's jurisdiction is limited to its geographic territory.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] However, online interactions are independent of geographic location and present across multiple locations, rendering the traditional concept of territorial sovereignty moot.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Therefore, the EU and the United States are forced to confront their regulatory differences and negotiate on a set of regulations that apply to all foreign companies processing and handling data of European citizens and residents.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] The regulatory differences on the right to be forgotten along with numerous other data protection rights have affected discussions and negotiations on trans-Atlantic data privacy regulations.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] A case in point is the EU and the United States' endeavors to develop the International Safe Harbor Privacy Principles agreement, a data transfer pact that enables the transfer of data between the EU and US companies in a manner consistent with the EU's data protection schemes.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Article 25 of the Data Protection Directive articulates that cross-border transfer of data can take place only if the "third country in question ensures an adequate level of protection," meaning that the country meets the EU's minimum standards of data protection.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] The standards include, among many provisions, a component that protects the right to "opt out" of further processing or transmission of personal data, with the assumption that data may not be further processed in ways inconsistent with the intent for which they were collected.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Given the inconsistencies between the EU and the United States on numerous digital privacy regulations, including the right to be forgotten, Article 25 poses a threat to trans-Atlantic data flows.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] As a result of the mass surveillance performed by the US government on European citizens' data, the Safe Harbor agreement has been invalidated by the European Union Court of Justice in its *Schrems* case.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] The Safe Harbor agreement has now been replaced by the Privacy Shield principles.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Businesses that manage their clients' online reputations have responded to the European Court ruling by exercising the right to be forgotten as a means to remove unfavorable information.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] One technique used by reputation consulting companies is to submit multiple requests for each link, written with different angles in an attempt to get links removed.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Google, for example, does not limit the number of requests that can be submitted on the removal of a given link.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Major criticisms stem from the idea that the right to be forgotten would restrict the right to freedom of speech.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Many nations, and the United States in particular (with the First Amendment to the United States Constitution), have very strong domestic freedom of speech laws, which would be challenging to reconcile with the right to be forgotten.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Some academics see that only a limited form of the right to be forgotten would be reconcilable with US constitutional law; the right of an individual to delete data that they have personally submitted.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] In this limited form of the right individuals could not have material removed that has been uploaded by others, as demanding the removal of information could constitute censorship and a reduction in the freedom of expression in many countries.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Sandra Coliver of the Open Society Justice Initiative argues that not all rights must be compatible and this conflict between the two rights is not detrimental to the survival of either.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] The draft General Data Protection Regulation was written broadly and this has caused concern.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] It has attracted criticism that its enactment would require data controlling companies to go to great lengths to identify third parties with the information and remove it.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] In addition to this, there are concerns about the requirement to take down information that others have posted about an individual; the definition of personal data in Article 4(2) includes "any information relating to" the individual.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] This, critics have claimed, would require companies to take down any information relating to an individual, regardless of its source, which would amount to censorship, and result in the big data companies eradicating much data to comply with this.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Such removal can impact the accuracy and ability of businesses and individuals to perform business intelligence, particularly due diligence to comply with anti bribery, anticorruption, and know your customer laws.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Other criticism revolves around the principle of accountability.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] There were concerns that the proposed General Data Protection Regulation would result in Google and other Internet search engines not producing neutral search results, but rather producing biased and patchy results, and compromising the integrity of Internet-based information.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Despite these criticisms and Google's action, the company's CEO, Larry Page worries that the ruling will be "used by other governments that aren't as forward and progressive as Europe to do bad things", though has since distanced himself from that statement.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] For example, pianist Dejan Lazic cited the "Right To Be Forgotten" in trying to remove a negative review about his performance from *The Washington Post*.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] He claimed that the critique was "defamatory, mean-spirited, opinionated, offensive and simply irrelevant for the arts". and the St.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Lawrence parish of the Roman Catholic church in Kutno, Poland asked Google to remove the Polish Wikipedia page about it, (in Polish) without any allegations mentioned therein as of that date.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Index on Censorship claimed that the *Costeja* ruling "allows individuals to complain to search engines about information they do not like with no legal oversight.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] This is akin to marching into a library and forcing it to pulp books.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Although the ruling is intended for private individuals it opens the door to anyone who wants to whitewash their personal history… The Court's decision is a retrograde move that misunderstands the role and responsibility of search engines and the wider Internet.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] In 2014, the Gerry Hutch page on the English Wikipedia was among the first Wikipedia pages to be removed by several search engines' query results in the European Union.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] *The Daily Telegraph* said, on 6 August 2014, that Wikipedia co-founder Jimmy Wales "described the EU's Right to be Forgotten as deeply immoral, as the organisation that operates the online encyclopedia warned the ruling will result in an Internet riddled with memory holes".
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Other commentators have disagreed with Wales, pointing to problems such as Google including links to revenge porn sites in its search results, and have accused Google of orchestrating a publicity campaign to escape the burdensome obligation to comply with the law.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] In response to the criticism, the EU has released a factsheet to address what it considers myths about the right to be forgotten.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] In addition to this, for further clarification of the law, the factsheet provides information about the important court case C-131/12 and frequently asked questions regarding Google, the purpose of the law, and how it works.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Other criticisms involving the right to be forgotten concerns the policies for data removal regarding minors.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] The U.S. has laws that protect the privacy of minors.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] The California Minor Eraser Law is a law that allows California residents younger than the age of 18 to request to have information removed that they posted on an online server.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] The law "applies to websites, social media sites, mobile apps and other online services" and follows "Europe's recognition of the 'right to be forgotten'".
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] This law became effective on January 1, 2015 and remains in existence.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Online "service" operators that have services "directed toward minors" must update their privacy policies to include the option to remove data if requested by a minor that is posted on a service.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] In the UK, the 2017 Conservative manifesto included a pledge to allow social media platform users to remove outdated information that was posted when they were younger than the age of 18.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] "A Tory victory on the 8th of June will lead to those youthful indiscretions on Facebook and Twitter being open to erasure.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] But there are also plans to fine social media firms for not moving at the speed of political opportunism over extreme content." The United Kingdom has not yet fully adopted the ruling of the European Court of Justice regarding the right to be forgotten and argued to keep it from becoming EU law.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] However, in the upcoming elections in the UK laws could be passed to allow minors to remove embarrassing posts or photos on social media that could come back to affect job applications or public image in later life.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Theresa May, then Prime Minister of the UK, has advocated to extend privacy rights for minors in allowing them to have a right to delete information.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] The intentions for this extension of privacy are based on the fact that social media sites store years of data that affect minors lives' much later after the information is posted.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] May gave her stance on privacy when she said, "'The Internet has brought a wealth of opportunity but also significant new risks which have evolved faster than society's response to them'".
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] The Conservative Party, which was headed by May from 2016 to 2019, has pushed for policies that aggressively remove illegal material from the Internet and fine firms that do not take action in removing said material.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] In 2015, Commission nationale de l'informatique et des libertés (CNIL) asked Google to remove data from all versions available in any part of the world.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Google and other entities argued that European data regulators should not be allowed to decide what Internet users around the world find when they use a search engine.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Security researchers from CISPA, Saarland University and the University of Auckland are working to develop software to support the automation of the right to be forgotten in a scalable, provable and privacy-preserving manner.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] The team's software, Oblivion, would automate the process of verifying someone's personal information can be found in a Google search result, to help Google staff manage the high volume of take-down requests.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Researchers have noted that the current capabilities of this technology have some limitations.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] The software can only determine whether a piece of information is available, not whether it should be removed.
[src:gdpr-technical-controls/right-to-be-forgotten] Data deletion protocols concerning the death of a user is another consideration.
